{"type":"message","id":"fb839a28","parentId":"359b0026","timestamp":"2026-04-14T02:13:44.190Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the situation clearly. Let me summarize:\n\n1. The `web_source_fusion_daily_latest.json` status was `FAILED_CLOSED` because `ths_web_selected_holdings_latest.json` was stale (from April 1st)\n2. The `enrich_holdings_with_prices.py` uses Tencent API (`qt.gtimg.cn`) - this is NOT the same as Tushare\n3. The \"SSL certificate issue\" mentioned in the task completion message is about the Tencent API, not Tushare\n4. 张玲 says she already gave the Tushare token yesterday and it was configured in `.zshrc` as `fa7fe5039b58853bd0df3fc31f1770fc4a8cfaa79c6bff0473829bbc`\n\n\n5. The environment variables aren't being loaded properly - `.zshrc` only runs for interactive shells while cron jobs and OpenClaw agents run in non-interactive contexts, so the Tushare token isn't available to the scripts\n\nThe real problem is that we need to make the Tushare token available to the `enrich_holdings_with_prices.py` script. I need to figure out whether to inject it via a Python wrapper script, create a wrapper that sets the environment variable before running the actual script, or directly modify the script itself. The `.zshrc` approach won't work since those scripts don't run in a login shell context, so I need to create a wrapper that sets the Tushare token before running the enrich script. Let me check if there's already a `cron_python.sh` wrapper in place that I can leverage for this.\n","thinkingSignature":"fedac3eb96101d00625fc6b55edf47bd080f8a1c66c9a12bd1d423d6d8f87c0e"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_kk1uo0q55k95_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/scripts/cron_python.sh"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_kk1uo0q55k95_2","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -n \"TUSHARE\\|tushare\\|export\" /Us