{"type":"message","id":"b864a167","parentId":"9bdd2970","timestamp":"2026-04-14T07:56:17.652Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see the problem clearly. The MKT_OK check in the cron script uses `urllib.request.urlopen` without SSL bypass, so when Python's SSL verification fails (because of the SSL certificate issue), the except block catches it and returns \"yes\" by default, thinking it's a trading day.\n\nBut that would mean it SHOULD have run... unless the cron job didn't even get to that point. Let me re-read:\n\n```python\nexcept:\n    print('yes')  # Default: assume trading day\n```\n\nThis means if SSL fails, it prints \"yes\" (trading day), so MKT_OK would be \"yes\" and the script should NOT skip. \n\nBut the log shows it DID skip. So either the cron job never ran at all today, or the SSL check succeeded but returned the wrong date. If the market date came back as something other than today, that would cause the skip.\n\nThe script calls `/usr/bin/python3` directly in the crontab, not the virtual environment's Python, so SSL verification failures would use the system certificate store. But here's the thing—the log only has an 08:25 entry, and there's also a 10:54 entry for something else. The intraday recheck script at 10:54 appears to have run, but I don't see any log output from it. That's odd.\n\nActually, looking at the timing, if there's no log entry for the intraday recheck at 10:54, maybe the job just didn't run that day. Or maybe it's running but not producing output. I should check if the cron jobs for intraday rebuild and paper trading actually exist and when they're scheduled to run.\n","thinkingSignature":"18896b0d7034ea5b1b5c3618b652640585aad30019d8fe816ccd456ebff7144f"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_hjuwcn5ksd1p_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"crontab -l 2>/dev/null | grep -i \"intraday\\|recheck\\|paper\\|trading\\|breadth\" 2>/dev/null"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_hj