{"type":"message","id":"f7a8aba0","parentId":"569d9691","timestamp":"2026-04-14T10:46:54.288Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I can see what happened:\n\n1. `generate_extended_predictions.py` was designed to **add predictions for April 1-11** to the existing file that ended at March 31\n2. It uses `cutoff = pd.Timestamp(\"2026-04-01\").date()` to only add predictions from April 1 onwards\n3. The script uses `qlib` with a GBDT model to generate new predictions for dates from April 1 to April 11\n\nBut the issue: **清明节（4月4日-6日）A股休市**，所以Qlib的特征数据里没有4月4日-6日的数据。当Qlib模型在清明节期间运行时，它无法获取这三天的数据。\n \nLooking at the actual predictions file from April 1-3, it contains thousands of entries per day with symbols like SZ002038 and 603538.SH. The real problem is that the script stopped generating predictions after April 3 because Qlib couldn't produce data for the holiday period when market features were unavailable.\n\nThe prediction file modification timestamp is April 13 at 00:24, but it only extends through April 3—meaning the `generate_extended_predictions.py` script either crashed or only partially completed when it tried to run. I should check the logs from that script to see what happened, and also verify whether there are any recent error logs from Qlib or the broader system that might explain the interruption.\n\nThe critical finding is that April 3 was the last day with predictions, and since then the prediction generation pipeline has been completely dormant. There's no daily cron job configured to run this script, so it was likely executed manually or triggered just once. To fix this, I need to first run `generate_extended_predictions.py` to get predictions current through today, then set up a daily cron job at 16:30 to keep predictions fresh going forward.","thinkingSignature":"71553b869261d450dac0c6b2f994de7dbf63c0768c2e54e6924f5531816d9b19"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_0yzvvmmc815n_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"