{"type":"message","id":"a4bf3705","parentId":"151b0741","timestamp":"2026-04-14T13:08:26.107Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting! The Qlib data for SH600000 and SZ000001 goes up to 04/08 only (not 04/10 as I thought earlier). Let me check what the actual latest date is.\n\n04/01, 04/02, 04/03, 04/07, 04/08 - that's it. Not 04/09 or 04/10. So Qlib is actually at 04/08 for individual stocks, but the calendar says 04/10.\n\nWait, this makes more sense! The calendar was updated by dump_update but the feature data wasn't. So:\n- Calendar: 04/10 (and now 04/14 after the last update)\n\n\n- Individual stocks: stuck at 04/08\n\nThe bin file is only 7044 bytes, which seems too small for years of daily data across 5 years—I'd expect around 1500+ records but we're only seeing about 587 records worth of space. So the file was already this size when it was originally created, which means it might actually be truncated or incomplete.\n\nThe file was modified today at 21:02, but the Qlib reader is only showing data through 04/08 even though there should be records up to 04/14. Let me read the bin file structure more carefully—the header should indicate the number of records, so I need to check what's actually stored in there.","thinkingSignature":"3fb0f62946c22131f45bdfd1874ca096f50ca02c9602dacde021ec45ea3a2afb"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_4ktcukcxyyq1_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"/usr/bin/python3 -c \"\n# Read the bin file as qlib would\nbin_path = '/Users/ling/.qlib/qlib_data/cn_data_long_2015_2026_180/features/SH600000/close.day.bin'\nimport struct\n\nwith open(bin_path, 'rb') as f:\n    content = f.read()\n\n# The qlib bin format: first 4 bytes = uint32 (little-endian) = number of records\nnum_records = struct.unpack('<I', content[:4])[0]\nprint(f'Num records header: {num_records}')\nprint(f'File size: {len(content)} bytes')\n\nif num_records == 0:\n    # Try big-endian\n    num_records_be = struct.unpac