{"type":"message","id":"f524dc74","parentId":"5b175ab4","timestamp":"2026-04-14T13:11:05.209Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand! The bin file has 880 records, but there should be 1760 records (one for each calendar day from 2019-01-02 to 2026-04-08). So the file is HALF of what it should be.\n\nWait, but 880 is exactly half of 1760. And the data I'm seeing shows:- Records 0-8: calendar indices 0, 7, 7, 7, 7, 7, 7, 7, 7 (all within the first week!)- Records around 870-880: all with index 10 (2019-01-16)This is very strange. \n\nAh, I see it now - the data must be stored as paired records where the first value is a time delta rather than an absolute index. The calendar probably uses business days only (skipping weekends and holidays), so the delta of 7 between records 0 and 1 makes sense if that's representing a 7-day calendar span in actual time.\n\nBut looking at the 880 records total, that's only about 3.6 years of data if each record represents a week's worth of accumulation, which doesn't align with having 1760 calendar entries. I need to reconsider whether the records are actually calendar-day deltas or if they're something else entirely—maybe they're accumulated return values rather than price indices themselves.","thinkingSignature":"9832e1aa23f3680692e1cbf4d039137580688fb5787bdf1785dbfaa23c7a9098"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_op7hvktpy19k_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"/usr/bin/python3 -c \"\nimport numpy as np\n\nbin_path = '/Users/ling/.qlib/qlib_data/cn_data_long_2015_2026_180/features/SH600000/close.day.bin'\ndata = np.frombuffer(open(bin_path, 'rb').read(), dtype=np.float32)\nn = len(data) // 2\n\n# Check first few records vs last few records\nprint('First 20 records (date_idx, close):')\nfor i in range(20):\n    idx = int(data[2*i])\n    print(f'  [{i:3d}] date_idx={idx:4d}: close={data[2*i+1]:.4f}')\n\nprint(f'\\\\nTotal records: {n}')\nprint(f'Expected records (calendar entries): ~1760')\n\n# Also check: what fraction of the file is read by Qlib?\n# Qlib D.features reads based on calendar, so it reads from index 0 to the latest\n# If file has 880 records, Qlib would only read up to calendar index 879\nprint(f'\\\\nCalendar index 879 = {open(\\\"/Users/ling/.qlib/qlib_data/cn_data_long_2015_2026_180/calendars/day.txt\\\").read().splitlines()[879]}')\nprint(f'Calendar index 880 = {open(\\\"/Users/ling/.qlib/qlib_data/cn_data_long_2015_2026_180/calendars/day.txt\\\").read().splitlines()[880]}')\nprint(f'Calendar index 1759 (last) = {open(\\\"/Users/ling/.qlib/qlib_data/cn_data_long_2015_2026_180/calendars/day.txt\\\").read().splitlines()[1759]}')\n\" 2>/dev/null"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":95059,"output":703,"cacheRead":35571,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":131333,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776172246208,"responseId":"062d6fda13315f7cc19a47b2d8240dba"}}
