{"type":"message","id":"5c67ca50","parentId":"53616763","timestamp":"2026-04-14T13:11:15.658Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the issue. The bin file has 880 records, which covers from calendar index 0 (2019-01-02) to calendar index 879 (2022-08-16). That's about 3.6 years of data.\n\nBut the ACTUAL data in Qlib for SH600000 goes up to 04/08 (calendar index 1759). This means the file should have 1760 records (one per calendar entry).\n\nWait - the Qlib data reading showed data up to 04/08 with 27 entries. But the bin file only has 880 records covering 2019-01-02 to 2022-08-16. \n\nThere's a massive discrepancy here. Either the file got corrupted, or Qlib is somehow reconstructing data from multiple sources rather than just reading this bin file directly. Let me check what the current file size actually is.","thinkingSignature":"af32ee2d98c8eb69957e6bd8524f7b8d5b57642ce695df022576d7cb002e8272"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_ag4onz4du9t6_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"stat -f \"%z %Sm\" ~/.qlib/qlib_data/cn_data_long_2015_2026_180/features/SH600000/close.day.bin 2>/dev/null || \\\nls -la ~/.qlib/qlib_data/cn_data_long_2015_2026_180/features/SH600000/close.day.bin\necho \"---\"\n# Also check if the bin file was recently overwritten\nmd5sum ~/.qlib/qlib_data/cn_data_long_2015_2026_180/features/SH600000/close.day.bin 2>/dev/null"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":96236,"output":334,"cacheRead":35571,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":132141,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776172265347,"responseId":"062d6fed1eff8f0c39459c336cd43b41"}}
{"type":"message","id":"dcadeddf","parentId":"5c67ca50","timestamp":"2026-04-14T13:11:15.785Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_ag4onz4du9t6_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"7044 Apr 14 21:02:13 2026\n---\ne88128e6edfb6269fdd5647418c69819  /Users/ling/.qlib/qlib_data/cn_data_long_2015_2026_180/features/SH600000/close.day.bin"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":38,"aggregated":"7044 Apr 14 21:02:13 2026\n---\ne88128e6edfb6269fdd5647418c69819  /Users/ling/.qlib/qlib_data/cn_data_long_2015_2026_180/features/SH600000/close.day.bin","cwd":"/Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/coding-agent"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1776172275769}}
{"type":"message","id":"114f208d","parentId":"dcadeddf","timestamp":"2026-04-14T13:11:31.966Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The file was last modified at 21:02:13 today (April 14), which is right after the dump_update ran at 21:00-21:01. The file was overwritten during the dump_update.\n\nBut the file is only 7044 bytes = 880 records = data up to 2022-08-16. This is clearly truncated/broken.\n\nThe issue might be with the UPDATE_MODE of dump_bin. When in UPDATE_MODE, it opens the existing file in \"ab\" (append) mode. But the file was already full (1760 records = 14080 bytes). If it opened in append mode, it would just add to the end. But if the original file was somehow replaced with a truncated version...\n \nWait, looking at the dump_bin code more carefully, I see it's using \"ab\" mode to append new records to the end of the existing file. The np.hstack operation is combining the date indices with the feature values, and I need to trace through what's actually being written versus what should be there.\n\nThe file went from 1760 records down to 880, which means something replaced the entire content rather than appending. The \"ab\" mode shouldn't overwrite, so either the file was recreated from scratch during this update, or there's something about how the UPDATE_MODE logic decides between appending and replacing that I'm missing.\n\nLet me step back and check if the bin files were accidentally deleted or replaced with truncated versions instead of the dump_update actually working correctly. The quickest fix would be to either completely rebuild the Qlib data from scratch or just replace the single stock's data file with a properly generated one.\n\nActually, I should first understand what went wrong with the dump_update command—it said it succeeded but the file is clearly corrupted. Let me test the dump_all command on just one stock to see if that works properly.","thinkingSignature":"44fbd5f29e150174cc01b12d43661872dd