{"type":"message","id":"18bdd5c0","parentId":"9b198c36","timestamp":"2026-04-14T13:12:21.769Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK so:\n- `/usr/bin/python3` = Python 3.9 (CommandLineTools)\n- `/usr/local/bin/python3` = Python 3.14\n- `python3` (without path) = Python 3.14 (via openclaw's environment)\n\nWhen I ran `cron_python.sh scripts/tushare_to_qlib_update.py --start ...`, the script used `sys.executable = /usr/local/bin/python3` (Python 3.14). This Python has qlib installed and the dump_bin.py works.\n\nWhen I ran `/usr/bin/python3 scripts/tushare_to_qlib_update.py ...`, the script used Python 3.9 which does NOT have qlib installed. The dump_bin.py failed because it couldn't be opened by Python 3.9.\n \nBut wait—the first run with `cron_python.sh` actually did succeed in updating the Qlib calendar to 04-10, so the script was working. The problem must be something else.\n\nLet me trace through what happened: when the CSV files were already present with cached data from 04-13 and 04-14, the download step correctly identified there was nothing new to fetch, then skipped ahead to the dump_update phase. The calendar got updated to 04-10 as expected, but then the second run with `/usr/bin/python3` tried to execute dump_bin.py and hit an error.\n\nActually, I need to reconsider—the second run with `/usr/bin/python3` invoked dump_bin.py directly rather than through the Python interpreter, so the shebang line would've been used instead. Since the script has `#!/usr/bin/env python3` at the top, it would've tried to run with Python 3.14 (the active version in that environment), which is where things went wrong.\n\nLooking at the error message more carefully: `can't open file '...dump_bin.py'` suggests the file itself doesn't exist or there's a path issue, not a Python version mismatch. And the subsequent verification showed the calendar is actually up to 2026-04-14 now, which is even more recent than what the second run should have p