{"type":"message","id":"9dd305e5","parentId":"e75eeebf","timestamp":"2026-04-14T13:40:25.737Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now it's perfectly clear:\n- Calendar: 1764 days (2019-01-02 ~ 2026-04-14)\n- All stock bin files: 1760 values, last date 2026-04-08\n- Missing data: 04-09, 04-10, 04-13, 04-14\n\nSo the Qlib data IS missing the most recent 4 trading days! The `tushare_to_qlib_update.py` ran successfully (according to its log) but didn't actually update the bin files with the new data from 04-09 onwards.\n \nThe issue is that when `tushare_to_qlib_update.py` checks for new dates, it finds 04-09 through 04-14 in the calendar but reports no updates are needed. This happens because `D.calendar()` returns all trading days in the range, but the actual bin files for each stock only contain data up to 04-08, so there's a mismatch between what the calendar thinks exists and what's actually in the data files. The universe file gets updated to include new stocks as of 04-14, but the existing bin files only contain data through 04-08, so there's a mismatch between what the calendar reports and what's actually stored. The update script skips writing bin files because it thinks the dates already exist, but that's not the real problem—the real issue is that the bin files themselves are incomplete for the dates they're supposed to cover.\n\nLooking at the calendar files, they're all updated through 04-14, but when I checked SH600000's bin file, it only had 1760 float32 values covering up to 04-08, when it should have 1764 to match the full calendar range. This suggests the bin files were correctly rebuilt at some point but then something caused them to be truncated or incompletely written.\n\nThe file timestamps show 04-14 21:02, which aligns with when `dump_update` ran, but the file size doesn't match what it should be. I need to figure out what the expected file size should be for the complete dataset through 04-14. So the bin files should span from index 0 to 1763, giving 1764 total records and a file size of 7060 bytes, but they only contain 1760 records (ending at 2026-04-08) with a size of 7044 bytes instead. This means the dump_update process added some new data but didn't fully extend the files to their expected length.\n\nI suspect what's happening is that `dump_update` regenerated the bin files with a new header and initial records but only wrote data for the rows that existed in the CSV, leaving the newer dates (04-09, 04-10, 04-13, 04-14) without corresponding records in the bin files.\n\nBut actually, I think the real issue is different. The CSV files do contain data for those newer dates—I can see 04-09 and 04-10 in the daily_20260410.csv file with 5495 rows. So the problem must be that `dump_update` isn't properly processing or including those dates when it writes to the bin files.\n\nLet me check if maybe `dump_update` only processes dates that fall within some update range or condition I haven't considered yet. I should look at what the daily_20260409 and daily_20260413 files actually contain to understand which dates have data in them.","thinkingSignature":"e367ab555eb67784b0e3bb22fcfdda7ce6a5fab46b61b180cd9b7d89d6dfd1a1"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_n7pl5bhw16e6_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"/usr/bin/python3 -c \"\nimport pandas as pd\nfrom pathlib import Path\n\nraw_dir = Path('/Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/data/tushare_raw')\nfor d in ['20260409', '20260410', '20260413', '20260414']:\n    f = raw_dir / f'daily_{d}.csv'\n    if f.exists():\n        df = pd.read_csv(f)\n        dates = df['date'].unique()\n        print(f'{d}: {len(df)} rows, dates: {dates}')\n\" 2>/dev/null"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":57590,"output":870,"cacheRead":39381,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":97841,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"tota