{"type":"message","id":"0536a503","parentId":"0589d61b","timestamp":"2026-04-14T14:49:03.584Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The issue is clear now - the first 10 stocks in the universe are all BJ stocks, and they have no data. The BJ stocks only have a few values in their bin files (6 for BJ920000). This means the BJ stock data wasn't appended for these dates (because the append script checks `n_existing >= N_CAL` and skips if the bin already has all 1764 values). But BJ920000 only has 6 values.\n\nWait, let me re-read the append script logic. The append script says:\n```python\nif n_existing >= N_CAL:\n    continue\n```\n\nFor BJ920000, `n_existing = 6`, `N_CAL = 1764`, so `6 >= 1764` is False, so it should have appended! But it didn't... because the `normalize_symbol` function in the append script uses `row['symbol'].upper()` which gives `'920000.BJ'` not `'BJ920000'`. \n \nI see the problem now - the append script never actually processed BJ stocks because the symbol normalization was producing the wrong format. When the CSV contains `920000.BJ`, converting it to uppercase gives `920000.BJ`, and then `sym_to_dir()` transforms that to `920000.bj` instead of `bj920000.bj`. The append script checks if the normalized symbol starts with `'#'` to skip header rows, so `920000.BJ` wouldn't be skipped, but it also wouldn't match the expected instrument format for the append logic to work correctly. So the condition `sym.startswith('BJ')` returns FALSE for `'920000.BJ'` - that's the bug. The append script never processed BJ stocks because it was checking for the wrong prefix after the symbol got converted to uppercase with the exchange suffix still attached.\n\nThe prediction script has the same issue - it's calling `sym_to_dir()` on symbols that still have the `.BJ` suffix, so the directory lookup fails. I need to normalize the CSV symbols first (stripping the `.BJ` part) before they reach `sym_to_dir()`.\n\nLooking at the actual