{"type":"message","id":"eceddce7","parentId":"def12d85","timestamp":"2026-04-14T14:49:36.987Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The BJ stocks only have 6 values, which means their bin files were created with only the first 6 calendar days (2019-01-02 to 2019-01-09). The dump_update never properly appended BJ stock data.\n\nThe issue is that the original dump_bin.py creates bin files for stocks based on the calendar, starting from the stock's first trading day. For BJ920000, its first trading day was 2019-05-24. But somehow the bin only has 6 values...\n\nWait, maybe the BJ stock data was never properly loaded into Qlib at all? Let me check the original `a_stock_daily_converted.csv` which was the source for the initial Qlib data creation. BJ stocks might not be in that file.\n\n\nActually, this is getting too tangled. The real problem is that my append script didn't work for BJ stocks because their bins are too short—they only contain a few values from 2019, not the full calendar range like SH and SZ stocks. I could fix this by deleting and recreating the BJ stock bins from the CSV data, but the most practical approach right now is to focus on SH and SZ stocks first since those are the mainstream A-shares anyway.\n\nLooking at the universe file, the SH and SZ stocks come after the BJ stocks, so I can target just those by filtering for stock codes starting with 'SH' or 'SZ'. The bin files for these stocks have the correct format and length (1760 values covering 2019-01-02 to 2026-04-08), so I just need to append the missing 4 values for the recent dates. Let me verify whether the append script actually ran correctly on the SH and SZ stocks.\n\nThe append script has a bug where it's normalizing CSV symbols to the format `'920000.BJ'` instead of `'BJ920000'`, so when it looks up data in the dictionary for BJ stocks, it fails to find matches. However, for SH and SZ stocks, the normalization works fine since there are no dots in those symbols, so the append should have succeeded for the mainstream stocks.\n\nNow I'm realizing the core issue: the universe contains about 5499 total stocks (306 BJ plus ~5193 SH/SZ), but if the append only processed SH/SZ stocks and skipped BJ stocks, then the SH/SZ stocks should have been updated correctly. Yet when I tested SH600000 on 2026-04-09, it showed no data. Let me trace through why the append might have failed for SH600000 specifically—the script reads the existing bin file, checks if it already has 1764 values, and if not, appends new values for each missing date.\n\nThe problem is likely that my test was looking at calendar index 1760, which corresponds to 2026-04-09 in a 1764-entry calendar, but the bin file might have a different internal structure or the date mapping is off.\n\nLet me reconsider the bin file format—the header specifies a start index (0 for SH600000), and the values array has 1760 entries, so for calendar index 1760 the script would try to access index 1760 of a 1760-element array, which is out of bounds. Either the bin files weren't actually appended with the new dates, or my calculation of which calendar index corresponds to 2026-04-09 is wrong.\n\nWait, looking back at the verification output showing the last 4 values as 9.93, 9.89, 9.86, 10.05 with corresponding dates through 2026-04-14—that's exactly 4 values matching the missing dates, so the append actually did work. The issue must be in how the prediction script is reading from these files.","thinkingSignature":"eccc2c5582a16328355032ba3cdf0652a859a4c1b2da8ecb46c5d18b961097cd"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_5rh0809v0ez1_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cd /Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system && \\\n/usr/bin/python3 << 'PYEOF'\n# Quick debug: trace exactly what read_stock_features does for SH600000 on 2026-04-09\nimport numpy as np\nfrom pathlib import Path\n\nQLIB_DATA_DIR = Path.home() / '.qlib/qlib_data/cn_data_lon