{"type":"message","id":"a71bfebf","parentId":"1fc7777c","timestamp":"2026-04-14T14:55:52.237Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I can see the data. The user's question is: why do some STALE/YELLOW (offline) accounts show better returns than some GREEN (active) accounts?\n\nLet me analyze:\n\n**GREEN (Active) accounts:**\n- v4.3_aggressive: date_tag=20260413, total_return_pct=-0.04% (almost zero)\n- defensive: date_tag=20260413, total_return_pct=0.59%\n- balanced: date_tag=20260413, total_return_pct=5.64%\n- aggressive: date_tag=20260413, total_return_pct=8.78%\n\n\n- breadth_aggressive: date_tag=2026-04-03, total_return_pct=5.02%\n\nThe breadth_aggressive account is marked YELLOW because its signal_date is 11 days old, yet it's still returning 5.02% — actually outperforming the active accounts except aggressive. Meanwhile, alpha55 is completely frozen with zero returns and a stale date from April 7th.\n\nLooking at the other frozen accounts, breadth_strict_oos shows -1.70% despite being offline since March 30th, while the exit_validation accounts (exit_dual and exit_tight) are both down around 3.66-3.68% and haven't updated since April 1st.\n\nThe user's confusion makes sense though—the breadth_aggressive account is performing well at 5.02% even though it's offline and using a \"signal_stale_hold\" mode, which means it's not actually trading new signals, so I need to understand what's driving that return.\n\nThe real issue seems to be a mismatch between what the user is observing in the HTML report versus what the JSON data shows. If the breadth accounts are showing good returns despite being offline, it could be that they held positions during the recent rally from April 3-13, and their final holdings happened to perform well on those dates, giving them unrealized gains that look artificially good compared to what they'd actually show if closed out.\n\nThe defensive and balanced accounts showing strong 5-9% returns while v4.3_aggressive shows near-zero returns on the same date is also striking—it suggests either very different position concentrations or that v4.3's holdings got wiped out in a drawdown during the period when predictions weren't being generated.\n\nI need to figure out what the user is actually seeing. They mentioned the offline paper accounts have the best returns, but looking at the data, breadth_aggressive at 5.02% isn't dramatically better than balanced at 5.64%. Let me trace through the breadth cron scripts to understand what was actually happening with those positions.","thinkingSignature":"ca42dfaf1dd3be95225edd149d33530b31519984a52b7b8914f3a5df9fb0d5cb"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_nnu85wkef9q2_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/research/reports/strategy_performance_panel_latest.json 2>/dev/null | python3 -c \"\nimport json, sys\nd = json.load(sys.stdin)\nrows = d.get('rows', [])\nprint(f'账号  最新  signal_date  total_return_pct  status  stale原因')\nprint('-'*80)\nfor r in rows:\n    freshness = r.get('freshness', {})\n    sig_date = r.get('date_tag', '?')\n    grp = r.get('group_label', '?')\n    name = r.get('short_name', '?')[:15]\n    ret = r.get('total_return_pct', 0)\n    status = r.get('status', '?')\n    status_reason = r.get('status_reason', '?')\n    print(f'{name:<16} sig={sig_date}  ret={ret:>6.2f}%  status={status}  reason={str(status_reason)[:30]}')\n\" 2>/dev/null"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":98915,"output":807,"cacheRead":35569,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":135291,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776178526182,"responseId":"062d885e1f2b8d2eba23fdeebd7e9b4c"}}
