{"type":"message","id":"cb8a9ae1","parentId":"189c3359","timestamp":"2026-04-14T15:30:05.471Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The config has `smallcap_live_candidates` which includes a profile and config. This might be loading the smallcap candidates which could be large. Let me check what the smallcap live candidates config looks like.\n\nActually, I think the issue is that in intraday mode, the system tries to load a lot of data (maybe from Qlib or from historical backtests). Let me take a different approach - instead of debugging the full chain, let me just check if the basic profile simulation runs for one small config.\n\nActually, let me look at the actual error. When the process gets SIGKILL, it means the OS killed it. On macOS, this can happen when:\n1. The system is low on memory (we have 16GB free... actually `Pages free: 167537` = ~2.7GB free, which is not that much)\n\n\n2. There's a per-process memory limit\n\nWait, I need to reconsider - the previous session output showed the process was still running after 280 seconds, then got killed. So it's not just an OOM issue - the process is actually hanging somewhere, possibly waiting on network or I/O.\n\nBut the current test also got SIGKILL after running for a while. Let me look at what's actually causing the hang in `prepare_paper_orders_v1.py` - it might be trying to fetch data from an API that's not responding.\n\nActually, the real issue might be simpler - I'm running this on macOS without timeout protection, and something in the execution config like `rd_agent_top2_gray` could be triggering external API calls. But the OOM fix I made earlier should have prevented heavy reports from loading. Yet the test still gets killed.\n\nI'm wondering if there's a macOS process isolation issue where child processes spawned via `cron_python.sh` aren't being cleaned up properly. Let me step back and run the intraday test again to see if it actually completes this time.\n\nWait, both attempts got SIGKILL - that's 9 minutes and 5 minutes respectively. This feels like a memory limit being hit. But the system's only using about 2.7GB out of 16GB available, so either the per-process limit is much lower, or one of the Python subprocesses is hitting its own memory ceiling.\n\nLooking at the flow more carefully: the intraday script calls through multiple layers - `run_paper_trading_profiles_auto_v1.sh` → `run_paper_trading_profiles_v1.sh` → individual Python scripts like `prepare_paper_orders_v1.py` and `run_paper_trading_sim_v1.py`. The real culprit might be `run_live_system_v1.py`, which gets called during the setup phase and could be loading something massive into memory.","thinkingSignature":"fc9edbb191bf981931171a0842054cf7e19f3b7166c9900e404be420c432afd8"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_6dzbuco1me58_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -n \"read_csv\\|pickle\\|DataFrame\\|concat\\|merge\\|np\\.load\" \\\n  /Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/scripts/run_live_system_v1.py 2>/dev/null | head -20\necho \"---\"\nwc -l /Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/scripts/run_live_system_v1.py"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":38885,"output":684,"cacheRead":35569,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":75138,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776180584629,"responseId":"062d90691d252e1e8890a11ffeb176b9"}}
