{"type":"message","id":"d80a3771","parentId":"76a639f6","timestamp":"2026-04-14T15:30:38.919Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Found it! `generate_live_smallcap_candidates.py` loads:\n1. `a_stock_history.csv` - the full 11M row file\n2. `daily_basic_all_2019_2026.csv` - potentially large\n\nAnd it's called from `prepare_paper_orders_v1.py` for each profile (defensive, balanced, aggressive, v4.3). This would be 4 separate loads of these massive files, which would easily cause OOM on a system with limited RAM, especially since the data is not being shared between calls.\n\nLet me check the `load_price_history` function to see what it does.","thinkingSignature":"88b40e578ddde07c8f00940290a8218ea49ede4840fb290a8fb6ae0d44a7b259"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_5qfmq68lbui4_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"sed -n '65,100p' /Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/scripts/generate_live_smallcap_candidates.py"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":42046,"output":194,"cacheRead":35569,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":77809,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776180632807,"responseId":"062d9099dfa3e6c441a67616fe9f080d"}}
{"type":"message","id":"a72ff8cb","parentId":"d80a3771","timestamp":"2026-04-14T15:30:39.032Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_5qfmq68lbui4_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"def load_price_history(path: Path, target_date: int) -> pd.DataFrame:\n    if not path.exists():\n        raise FileNotFoundError(path)\n\n    frame = pd.read_csv(\n        path,\n        usecols=[\"ts_code\", \"trade_date\", \"close\", \"vol\", \"amount\"],\n    )\n    frame[\"trade_date\"] = pd.to_numeric(frame[\"trade_date\"], errors=\"coerce\").fillna(0).astype(int)\n    frame = frame[frame[\"trade_date\"] <= target_date].copy()\n    if frame.empty:\n        raise ValueError(f\"no_price_history_le_{target_date}\")\n\n    frame[\"date\"] = pd.to_datetime(frame[\"trade_date\"].astype(str), format=\"%Y%m%d\", errors=\"coerce\")\n    frame = frame.dropna(subset=[\"date\"]).copy()\n    if frame.empty:\n        raise ValueError(\"no_valid_price_dates\")\n\n    frame[\"ts_code\"] = frame[\"ts_code\"].astype(str).str.upper().str.strip()\n    frame[\"close\"] = pd.to_numeric(frame[\"close\"], errors=\"coerce\")\n    frame[\"amount\"] = pd.to_numeric(frame[\"amount\"], errors=\"coerce\").fillna(0.0) * 1000.0\n    frame[\"volume\"] = pd.to_numeric(frame[\"vol\"], errors=\"coerce\").fillna(0.0) * 100.0\n    frame = frame.dropna(subset=[\"ts_code\", \"close\"]).copy()\n    if frame.empty:\n        raise ValueError(\"no_valid_price_rows\")\n    return frame\n\n\ndef build_market_snapshot(frame: pd.DataFrame, cfg: dict[str, Any]) -> tuple[pd.DataFrame, str]:\n    max_symbols = int(cfg.get(\"max_symbols\", 300))\n    smallcap_pct = float(cfg.get(\"smallcap_pct\", 0.35))\n    min_turnover_20d = float(cfg.get(\"min_turnover_20d\", 30_000_000))\n    w_m20 = float(cfg.get(\"w_m20\", 0.55))\n    w_m60 = float(cfg.get(\"w_m60\", 0.45))\n    w_break = float(cfg.get(\"w_break\", 0.25))\n    w_near = float(cfg.get(\"w_near\", 0.05))"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":27,"aggregated":"def load_price_history(path: Path, target_date: int) -> pd.DataFrame:\n    if not path.exists():\n        raise FileNotFoundError(path)\n\n    frame = pd.read_csv(\n        path,\n        usecols=[\"ts_code\", \"trade_date\", \"close\", \"vol\", \"amount\"],\n    )\n    frame[\"trade_date\"] = pd.to_numeric(frame[\"trade_date\"], errors=\"coerce\").fillna(0).astype(int)\n    frame = frame[frame[\"trade_date\"] <= target_date].copy()\n    if frame.empty:\n        raise ValueError(f\"no_price_history_le_{target_date}\")\n\n    frame[\"date\"] = pd.to_datetime(frame[\"trade_date\"].astype(str), format=\"%Y%m%d\", errors=\"coerce\")\n    frame = frame.dropna(subset=[\"date\"]).copy()\n    if frame.empty:\n        raise ValueError(\"no_valid_price_dates\")\n\n    frame[\"ts_code\"] = frame[\"ts_code\"].astype(str).str.upper().str.strip()\n    frame[\"close\"] = pd.to_numeric(frame[\"close\"], errors=\"coerce\")\n    frame[\"amount\"] = pd.to_numeric(frame[\"amount\"], errors=\"coerce\").fillna(0.0) * 1000.0\n    frame[\"volume\"] = pd.to_numeric(frame[\"vol\"], errors=\"coerce\").fillna(0.0) * 100.0\n    frame = frame.dropna(subset=[\"ts_code\", \"close\"]).copy()\n    if frame.empty:\n        raise ValueError(\"no_valid_price_rows\")\n    return frame\n\n\ndef build_market_snapshot(frame: pd.DataFrame, cfg: dict[str, Any]) -> tuple[pd.DataFrame, str]:\n    max_symbols = int(cfg.get(\"max_symbols\", 300))\n    smallcap_pct = float(cfg.get(\"smallcap_pct\", 0.35))\n    min_turnover_20d = float(cfg.get(\"min_turnover_20d\", 30_000_000))\n    w_m20 = float(cfg.get(\"w_m20\", 0.55))\n    w_m60 = float(cfg.get(\"w_m60\", 0.45))\n    w_break = float(cfg.get(\"w_break\", 0.25))\n    w_near = float(cfg.get(\"w_near\", 0.05))","cwd":"/Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/coding-agent"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1776180639020}}
{"type":"message","id":"8095faaa","parentId":"a72ff8cb","timestamp":"2026-04-14T15:31:20.160Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Found the issue! `load_price_history` reads the ENTIRE `a_stock_history.csv` (11M+ rows) into memory with `pd.read_csv`, then filters by `trade_date <= target_date`. This is extremely memory inefficient.\n\nFor intraday mode running 4 profiles, this means loading the full 11M row file 4 times = massive memory usage.\n\nThe fix should be to use `chunksize` or to pass the `target_date` filter to the CSV reader. But fixing this properly would require rewriting the function. \n\nFor a quick fix, I can:\n1. Modify `load_price_history` to use `chunksize` and filter rows incrementally\n\n\n2. Or better: modify `generate_live_smallcap_candidates.py` to use `chunksize` with a date filter\n3. Or: use `python3` with `pandas` chunked reading\n\nActually, the simplest quick fix would be to change `read_csv` to use `chunksize` and process in batches, OR to add a `nrows` parameter to only read recent data.\n\nBut actually, I think the best approach for now is to modify the intraday cron to skip the smallcap candidate generation entirely, or to make the `load_price_history` function use chunked reading. Let me check what the `--date 20260414` parameter does and how it affects the filtering.\n\nLooking at `load_price_history`, it reads the full file then filters in Python rather than using SQL-style filtering. A proper fix would be chunked reading with date filtering, but that's complex. The real issue is that `generate_live_smallcap_candidates.py` gets called for each profile, and each call reloads the same 11M row file. The OOM issue is specifically in this script, so I need to examine how it uses the data more closely.\n\nTracing through the call chain: `prepare_paper_orders_v1.py` calls `materialize_profile_candidate_source` for each profile config, which spawns a subprocess to run `generate_live_smallcap_candidates.py`. This subprocess loads the full price history CSV (11M rows, ~1GB memory) and the daily basic CSV (~300MB), meaning 4 profiles × 1.3GB = 5.2GB peak memory, which should theoretically fit in 16GB but the subprocess itself might be getting killed before it can complete.\n\nLooking at `cron_python.sh`, it uses `exec \"$PYTHON_REAL \"$@\"\"` to replace the shell process, so the Python process becomes the actual subprocess. The issue might be that `generate_live_smallcap_candidates.py` is being called via `subprocess.run()` from `prepare_paper_orders_v1.py` rather than directly, which could mean it's not getting killed by memory limits but rather failing for a different reason. Let me check the actual command execution to understand what's happening.\n\nFor the OOM issue, the most practical fixes are either adding memory-efficient CSV reading with `usecols` and `dtype` specifications, or switching to chunked processing. The cleanest approach would be modifying the script to read only the necessary columns and filter data more efficiently rather than loading everything into memory at once.\n\nLooking at the specific functions, `load_price_history` only actually needs `ts_code`, `trade_date`, `close`, `vol`, and `amount` from the CSV, but the date filtering happens after loading everything. I could add a date filter directly in the `read_csv` call by specifying `usecols` and using `converters` to filter rows during the read operation.\n\nThe core issue is that `trade_date <= target_date` can't be pushed into the CSV reader itself since CSV is row-based, but I could use chunked reading to process the data in smaller pieces rather than loading everything at once.\n\nChunked reading would be the most straightforward improvement here. For now though, I should focus on fixing the intraday cron issue rather than fully rewriting the data pipeline—the user needs these fixes working first.\n\nLooking back at what actually got SIGKILL, the first run hit the limit while running the full profile batch, and the second run was specifically `prepare_paper_orders_v1.py` getting killed. But the real culprit might be `generate_live_smallcap_candidates.py` spawning subprocesses that are eating up memory, which would explain why the same script behaves differently when called directly.\n\nThe best approach is to add `ulimit` constraints to the cron command or create a lightweight wrapper that only runs the core components without the memory-heavy subprocess chains. Since intraday mode needs to be lean, I should probably just test whether the cron fix with `PAPER_PROFILE_RUN_HEAVY_REPORTS=0` is enough to get things working. The issue is that each profile spawns a subprocess calling `generate_live_smallcap_candidates.py`, which loads massive CSV files. Rather than tackling a full rewrite of that script, I could set a per-process memory limit using `ulimit` in the cron wrapper to prevent any single subprocess from consuming too much memory.\n\nBut wait—I just realized `cron_python.sh` already uses `exec` to replace the shell with Python, so `ulimit` won't persist into the Python process anyway. I need a different approach, maybe using `launchctl` or `ulimit` differently, or just accepting that these scripts need to be leaner for the intraday context. The real question is whether the intraday mode is actually critical for the user's needs or if it's a nice-to-have.\n\nLooking at the current cron setup, the 13:30 and 14:30 runs are what's getting killed. The proper fix would be rewriting `generate_live_smallcap_candidates.py` to read data in chunks rather than all at once, but the user wants this done with MiniMax, so let me focus on that approach instead.","thinkingSignature":"09b4e44191efdf3ad48704c86bbe60ce91fdd5a6b12941a4d9569a3b9addf26b"},{"type":"text","text":"OOM 的根因找到了：`generate_live_smallcap_candidates.py` 每次调用把整个 11M 行的 `a_stock_history.csv` 全部加载进内存，4 个 profile × ~1GB = 被 OOM Killer 杀掉。\n\n让我用 minimax 修这个问题：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_