{"type":"message","id":"a1b668de","parentId":"8c9eaecc","timestamp":"2026-04-14T15:38:27.696Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good. Now I need to:\n1. Fix `generate_predictions_lite_v3.py` to use `CAL[-1]` as the default PRED_END (dynamic)\n2. Fix the time order issue - the pipeline needs to generate predictions BEFORE the paper trading runs the next day\n\nFor P0-2, the real fix is:\n- Pipeline at 16:30 generates predictions for dates up to today (2026-04-14)\n- Next day 08:30 breadth paper trading uses 04-14 predictions\n\nCurrently:\n- PRED_END is hardcoded to 04-13, so pipeline would generate 04-13 predictions\n- 08:30 paper uses yesterday's predictions (which would be 04-13 if generated yesterday at 16:30)\n\n\n- But the pipeline won't actually run today yet at 16:30 since it's already past that time\n\nSo I need to fix PRED_END to pull dynamically from the calendar, and the time order should resolve itself once the pipeline runs at 16:30 today and generates 04-14 predictions for the 08:30 paper trading tomorrow.\n\nWait, I'm seeing a potential issue with the PRED_START date. It's hardcoded to 04-07, which is already in the past. When the pipeline runs tomorrow at 16:30, it'll try to generate predictions from 04-07 onwards, but those historical predictions already exist in the CSV. I need to check what the CSV currently has and understand how the append logic handles duplicates.\n\nLooking at the script structure, it reads the existing CSV, filters for new trading dates between PRED_START and PRED_END that aren't already in the existing data, then trains and generates predictions only for those new dates. So the fix is straightforward: change PRED_END from a hardcoded date to use the calendar's last date instead. PRED_START should probably stay hardcoded since we only need the most recent predictions.\n\nNow I'm realizing the real issue is the time ordering—the breadth paper cron at 08:30 runs before the daily pipeline at 16:30, so it's always working with stale data from the previous day. But that's actually the right behavior for a trading system: the pipeline generates today's predictions after market close at 16:30, and the next morning's paper trading uses those predictions to execute orders. So the sequence is correct—today's close generates predictions that drive tomorrow's trading.\n\nThe GPT-5.4 report flagged this as \"time dependency inversion\" because the signal is always one day behind, but that's by design in a historical backtest system, not a bug. What actually matters is whether PRED_END is dynamic and whether the 16:30 pipeline finishes before the next morning's 08:30 run.","thinkingSignature":"c81ab49c9a90b6850f0cde32bbadfd83bfc6af6468141e08b7f5522b552cfb38"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_odxcx8bj4fnh_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# 修复 PRED_END 硬编码\nsed -n '20,30p' /Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/scripts/generate_predictions_lite_v3.py"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":51699,"output":635,"cacheRead":35391,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":87725,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776181089082,"responseId":"062d926160ca5633abaef768cdf4cfa3"}}
